The old saying "happy wife, happy life" is not applicable to me, or my relationship, and it's toxic. To me, both spouses deserve to be happy in a relationship. The belief that only the wife's happiness matters overlooks the fact that men also have emotions and desires that need to be fulfilled.

A relationship is a partnership between two people, and both individuals should be able to pursue their own happiness. When one partner is unhappy, it affects the entire relationship and can lead to tension and conflict. On the other hand, when both partners are happy, it creates a positive and harmonious environment that benefits the entire relationship.

Happiness is not a one-sided affair, and men deserve happiness too. Society has often perpetuated toxic masculine stereotypes that discourage men from expressing their emotions and seeking happiness. This is damaging to both men and their relationships. All individuals, regardless of gender, should feel free to pursue happiness and have their well-being prioritized in their relationships. ❤️

One of the things that I’m proud of is how I’ve kept the promise to myself to continue to work out throughout my pregnancy. Do I always feel like it? No. Do I want to lay in bed longer most days? Yes. 

I’m thankful that I’ve been able to do this in a healthy way, gain minimal weight and continue to do one of the things that makes me happy and healthy. 💪🏾✨ 

Scroll to see how I’ve transformed over the last couple of months 😅 and yes I love my beats! 🎧 #fitpregnancy

I've Never Felt more beautiful. 🥺 Pregnancy is such a beautiful sacred experience, a gift, and I love it here. 🤍

Someone recently asked how I’ve been able to stay in such good spirits and have so much joy and these are just some things that have worked for me…

1. I love being pregnant and think it's the best thing ever but that's just me and my experience... I think having a positive attitude & being thankful about anything makes the experience even more amazing.

2. My pregnancy hasn’t been complicated. I often forget I’m pregnant until I look down or in the mirror. 

3. I have an amazing husband who doesn’t play about me and advocates for me. ❤️

4. I hired Women of Color/women to be apart of my care team. 🥺💪🏾🩷 Worth every dime. 

My OBGYN is AMAZING.
My Doula is AMAZING.
My Physical therapist is AMAZING.
My Chiropractor is AMAZING. 

5. I’m a planner and type A. My birth plan was done by the end of my first trimester, hospital tours and classes have been done/started, hospital bag is already packed… when you plan you can really enjoy everything better in my opinion. 

6. I PUT ME FIRST. I’m not missing a workout, massage, hair, or toe appointment. 

7. I’ve been documenting my journey. Doing weekly photo shoots have really helped me to get back into creating content I enjoy, dressing up even when I don't feel like it, working with some cool brands, and modeling low key. 

8. I’ve put more time into my hobbies. I’ve started crafting more and dissociating from things that don’t truly bring out my creativity. 

9. I’ve kept my boundaries. Keeping the same boundaries and peace I had prior to pregnancy, only controlling what I can, staying in my place of peace, and doing the same things I love and enjoy.

Was looking at some things that came across my feed last week and let's talk…

As a black woman…It's not enough that your provider looks like you. 

Every time I have an appointment with my OBGYN or any of the physicians in my rotation I have my birth plan with me because it is that serious. We walk through the birth plan together line by line because it is that serious and acceptance will be acknowledged on the day of delivery. (Whether verbal or written regardless of the changes that will be made or not.)

Every time you go for an appointment ask questions how they ask you because it is that serious. We, me and my husband ask all the questions and don't back down when they ask questions even if we aren't knowledgeable in a certain area or understand what they are asking or why because it is that serious. 

As a black woman, you don't need to be intimidated by people you're paying. You don't need to just go along with something because they are telling you to do it or it's important…etc, do your research and be the annoying patient if you have to. You need to know that they are good and qualified for the impact that they could potentially have on you and your child's life. 

As a black woman bringing a child into this world, you need to be comfortable with everyone who has a role to play in you and your child's life and they need to know that you mean business and you're not playing with you or your child's life. 

As a black woman, you deserve to walk out of the hospital with your life and your child…

No one talks about the fact that as you become a parent there's a lot of processing and analyzing that takes place. It's truly an experience and a GROWING process. It's like the realities of what you experienced growing up hit you at once and you start replaying…EVERYTHING….good and bad. Memories and things that I haven't thought about in over 10-20 years…have come up. 

This has led me to do a lot of analyzing and examining of…people and seeing them for who they truly are...just people. People without an emotional attachment, title, or relationship…just people. 

This has also led me to look into some of the things said and done to me in my childhood &...I would NEVER.  My child will never have to deal with 1/4 of the stuff I saw or experienced and it truly makes me sick to my stomach even thinking about it and thinking about all the adults who had a role to play in it negatively…knowingly. 

While this process makes you look at almost everyone sideways and become even more protective over what you have and what you are producing I'm thankful. Thankful for this time and the ability to fully analyze and process my childhood to become an amazing mother, break off any toxic generational curses/cycles, grow, separate from dysfunctional people in every capacity, and I love that my child won't have a childhood they'll have to heal or recover from as long as I'm on this earth.🤍

So yeah, I'm back to my favorite protective style, not cutting my hair anymore if you’re thinking about cutting your hair…think really deeply about all that will come with it, or don’t do it! Don't allow these hair pages with all the cute cuts, styles, and not knowing what to do with your hair get you. 😅

Yesterday, October 4th made it one year from one of the days I will never forget. I told God if he brought me through the last year I would tell our testimony and here I am…telling our testimony.😭

If I could change anything about the last 12 months I honestly wouldn’t change a thing. While the season before our current one was rough, it grew both of us individually, and collectively, our marriage, our future family, our ministry, our relationships, and ultimately our faith. God is a REDEEMER!

After 2 early losses, a D&C, tears, worrying, waiting, and so much more …we sought out a fertility clinic to begin IVF and after a series of genetic tests, cancer panels, giving so much blood, and so many screenings were basically told that we were 100% healthy and it just happens…unexplained and to try again…AGAIN.

At this point, my husband kept his faith but mine was no longer there…I personally felt like Job. For the first time in my life, I felt like less of a woman, and I felt like I literally had no control over something I should have…it was rough. It really tested me/us in a way that we never experienced. 

In this season I learned how important it was that I married a man who not only knew God but had a relationship with God because when I was weak…he carried me spiritually and physically…literally. I also learned so much about myself, and my faith, and that sometimes God wants you to just try again and will allow certain things to happen for his glory and to make you into who he needs you to be… I learned about God in a new way. 

After many tears, tests, challenges, and coming to terms that it wasn’t us, it wasn’t our fault, and that it just..” happens”…we contended for our future family and sought God for what he wanted us to do. We started seeing a Christian ND, and a new OB (another story for another day…), cleaned up our diet, cut out all kinds of junk, released some things, prayed, fasted, and really gave it to God…fully surrendered.

I’ll share more as God leads us but through this experience not only will we be welcoming our miracle soon but we know God as a Redeemer… a Waymaker…a Promise Keeper even more than before. 🥺❤️

How it’s going vs How it started hair edition✨

I’ve been getting messages about my hair so let’s talk about hair…All my life my hair has been super thick and unmanageable for me. In 2019 I got frustrated with my hair and decided to big chop after years of perming it to get rid of all the damaged hair, kept it short for a few months, and now here we are. I do have a few heat-damaged pieces but it doesn’t bother me. My goal is to grow it to tailbone length over the next 2 years and now that I have a daughter I want her to love her natural hair. I have to be an example of that. 💕

Things that I’ve done to help with growing it:

1. Found stylists to do it for me and wear protective styles. It aids in not being frustrated or getting hair depressed. This was my issue before. I was trying to do it myself. 
2. Found a style that I can do easily when it’s not in a protective style. Right now that’s a braid out. 
3. Leaving it alone. When it’s in sew-ins I don’t put heat on my hair until I have to go somewhere. That’s 1-2 times a week…if that tbh.
4. Washing it every 2 weeks. I use @tresemme and @sheamoisture products

That’s it. How are you managing and growing your natural hair? ✨

Still so dreamy! 🤍
